ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think="This is very important! The `InitialSchema` migration defines `user_p
rofiles` with `user_id` as PRIMARY KEY (no separate `id` column), and uses `age_
range_min`/`age_range_max`. But the `CreateUsersAndUserProfiles` migration defin
es it with `id` as PRIMARY KEY and `user_id` as a separate column, and uses `pre
ferred_min_age`/`preferred_max_age`.\n\nThere are TWO migrations for the same ta
bles! This is a conflict. The `InitialSchema` was run first (same timestamp but 
alphabetically first), then `CreateUsersAndUserProfiles` would try to create the
tables again but with `IF NOT EXISTS`, so it would be a no-op.\n\nThis means the
ACTUAL DB schema is the one from `InitialSchema`:\n- `user_profiles.user_id` is 
PRIMARY KEY\n- No `id` column\n- No `avatar_url` column  \n- `age_range_min` and
`age_range_max` (not preferred_min_age)\n- `latitude` is DECIMAL(10,8) and `long
itude` is DECIMAL(11,8)\n\nWait, but `CreateUsersAndUserProfiles` has `IF NOT EX
ISTS`, so if `InitialSchema` ran first, the tables already exist and `CreateUser
sAndUserProfiles` does nothing. So the actual schema matches `InitialSchema`.\n\
nBut the auth module's entity expects `id` as PK, `avatar_url`, `userId` as a re
gular column, `preferredMinAge` mapping to `preferred_min_age`. This entity is W
RONG for the actual DB schema!\n\nThis is a major bug in the existing codebase. 
The auth service creates a profile with `id` and `userId`, but the actual DB tab
le doesn't have an `id` column - it has `user_id` as PK.\n\nLet me verify this b
y checking the data-source config to see migration order.",
    encrypted=None
)
