ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think="Looking at AdminService, it uses QueryBuilder with raw SQL joins, so 
it doesn't actually use the UserProfileEntity mapping for the query - it just ne
eds the repository to exist. But the entity mapping is still registered with Typ
eORM.\n\nThis is a codebase with some inconsistencies. For the profile feature, 
I need to be pragmatic. The simplest approach that won't break existing auth fun
ctionality:\n\n1. Create the profile module using the SAME entities as the auth 
module (camelCase with `name:` mapping). I can import them from `../auth/entitie
s/...`\n2. Or, I can add profile endpoints directly to the auth module\n\nActual
ly, looking at the plan, it says to create `apps/api/src/modules/profile/`. The 
cleanest way is to create the profile module and import the auth entities. Since
the auth module doesn't export them, I can directly import them from the auth mo
dule's entity files. This is a relative import within the same project, which is
fine.\n\nWait, but `TypeOrmModule.forFeature([UserProfileEntity, UserPhotoEntity
])` in ProfileModule would try to register entities that are already registered 
by AuthModule. With `autoLoadEntities: true`, TypeORM should handle this by not 
duplicating. Actually, `autoLoadEntities` works by collecting all entities passe
d to `forFeature` and registering them. If the same class is passed twice, it mi
ght cause issues.\n\nLet me think about this differently. I can:\n1. Update Auth
Module to also export the entities (add `TypeOrmModule` to exports)\n2. Then Pro
fileModule can import `AuthModule` and use the repositories without re-registeri
ng\n\nActually, in NestJS, if AuthModule exports `TypeOrmModule`, then ProfileMo
dule can import AuthModule and inject repositories for UserProfileEntity and Use
rEntity. Let me check if this is the standard pattern.\n\nYes! The standard patt
ern is:\n```typescript\n@Module({\n  imports: [TypeOrmModule.forFeature([UserEnt
ity, UserProfileEntity])],\n  exports: [TypeOrmModule], // This makes the reposi
tories available to importing modules\n})\nexport class AuthModule {}\n```\n\nTh
en ProfileModule can import AuthModule and inject `@InjectRepository(UserProfile
Entity)`.\n\nThis would be the cleanest fix. I'll modify AuthModule to export Ty
peOrmModule, then create ProfileModule importing AuthModule.\n\nLet me now plan 
the implementation. I need to implement:\n1. Backend: Profile module (controller
, service, DTOs)\n2. Backend: Photo module (controller, service, DTOs) \n3. Back
end: OSS module (controller, service, DTOs)\n4. Backend: ProfileCompletionGuard\
n5. Backend: Update auth module to export TypeOrmModule\n6. Mobile: Profile setu
p page, profile edit page, profile BLoC\n7. Tests: BDD features and steps\n8. AP
I contracts\n\nLet me also check the existing mobile structure more carefully.",
    encrypted=None
)
